''Marquee Moon'' has since been cited by rock critics as one of the greatest albums of the American [[punk rock]] movement,{{sfn|Brown|Newquist|1997|p=157}} including Mark Weingarten of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', who called it the masterpiece of the 1970s [[Punk rock#New York City|New York punk rock]] scene.<ref name="Weingarten"/> ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' called it the CBGB era's "best and most enduring record", and ranked it as sixth greatest album of all time in 1987.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The 25 Greatest Albums of All Time|journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|location=New York|page=46|volume=5|issue=1|month=April|year=1989|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=h-bxxO5B-xsC&pg=PA47#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=March 31, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Q magazine|Q]]'' magazine gave it five stars in a retrospective review and included it in their 2002 list of the 100 greatest punk albums,<ref name="Qmag"/> while ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' ranked it 35th on a similar list in 2003.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=Mojo|month=March|year=2003|page=76|title=Top 50 Punk Albums|location=London}}</ref> In a 2004 review for ''[[Tracks (magazine)|Tracks]]'', Christgau called ''Marquee Moon'' "the must-have<U+2014>one of the great debut albums, period."<ref>{{cite journal|last=Christgau|first=Robert|month=January|year=2004|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cdrev/televisi-tra.php|title=Television: Marquee Moon/Adventure/Live at the Old Waldorf|journal=[[Tracks (magazine)|Tracks]]|location=St Leonards, New South Wales|accessdate=March 31, 2013|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6G41wYlqT|archivedate=April 22, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> It was named one of the greatest albums of the 1970s by ''NME'', who ranked it tenth,<ref>{{cite journal|journal=NME|date=Steptember 18, 1993|page=19|location=London|title=The Greatest Albums Of The '70s}}</ref> and [[Pitchfork Media]], who ranked it third.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/5932-top-100-albums-of-the-1970s/10/|title=Staff Lists: Top 100 Albums of the 1970s|date=June 23, 2004|publisher=Pitchfork Media|accessdate=August 9, 2011|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6G41ydyKK|archivedate=April 22, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> In 2003, ''NME'' ranked ''Marquee Moon'' as the fourth greatest album of all time,<ref>{{cite journal|date=March 8, 2003|pages=35<U+2013>42|title=NME's 100 Best Albums of All Time!|journal=NME|location=London}}</ref> and ''Rolling Stone'' placed it at number 128 on their list of [[500 Greatest Albums of All Time|the 500 greatest albums of all time]].<ref>{{cite journal|date=November 1, 2003|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20090708064226/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/6598703/128_marquee_moon|title=128) Marquee Moon|journal=Rolling Stone|location=New York|accessdate=April 22, 2013|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6G8bwQ0kY|archivedate=April 25, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> It has been viewed as one of the greatest rock albums of all time by [[Marc Riley]], who said that "there's been nothing like it before or since," and [[Mark Radcliffe]], who called it "the nearest rock record to a [[string quartet]] - everybody's got a part, and it works brilliantly."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/friday_review/story/0,3605,448649,00.html|title=Home entertainment: Mark and Lard|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|date=March 9, 2001|accessdate=May 29, 2013|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6GzQy9JY2|archivedate=May 29, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref>

=== Alternative rock ===
''Marquee Moon'' was also one of the most influential albums recorded in the 1970s,{{sfn|Martin et al.|2003|p=1060}} and has been cited by critics as a cornerstone of [[alternative rock]].{{sfn|Moon|2008|p=770}} It heavily influenced the [[indie rock]] movement of the 1980s, while post-punk acts appropriated the album's precise instrumentation, uncluttered production, and introspective tone.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Woodhouse|first=Alan|date=August 3, 2012|url=http://www.nme.com/blog/index.php?blog=154&title=most_important_albums_of_nme_s_lifetime__1&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1|title=Most Important Albums Of NME's Lifetime - Television, 'Marquee Moon'|journal=NME|location=London|accessdate=April 1, 2013|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6G8c6jAeG|archivedate=April 25, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> Music critic [[Piero Scaruffi]] credited the album for defining the musical aesthetic of [[new wave music|New Wave]] with its unsettling melodies and [[free jazz]]-inspired group jamming.{{sfn|Scaruffi|2003|p=166}} Hunter Felt of [[PopMatters]] attributed the album's influence on post-punk and New Wave acts to the precisely [[syncopation|syncopated]] rhythm section of Fred Smith and Billy Ficca, and recommended 2003's "definitive" reissue of the album to listeners of [[garage rock revival]] bands, whom he said had modeled themselves after Verlaine's [[Romantic poetry]]-inspired lyrics and the "jaded yet somehow impassioned cynicism" of his vocals.<ref>{{cite web|last=Felt|first=Hunter|date=September 22, 2003|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/television-marquee2003/|title=Television: Marquee Moon <nowiki>[remastered edition]</nowiki>|publisher=[[PopMatters]]|accessdate=April 1, 2013|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6G8cjnMl7|archivedate=April 25, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref>

According to [[Sputnikmusic]]'s Adam Downer, the album "introduced the world to post-punk" with its unprecedented style of rock and roll.<ref name="Downer">{{cite web|last=Downer|first=Adam|date=September 29, 2006|url=http://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/9340/Television-Marquee-Moon/|title=Review: Television - Marquee Moon|publisher=[[Sputnikmusic]]|accessdate=April 1, 2013|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6G41WBMZH|archivedate=April 22, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' said that it scaled "amazing new heights of sophistication and intensity" as a "gorgeous, ringing beacon of post-punk, even if it did come out six months before ''[[Never Mind the Bollocks]]''."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2007/nov/22/1000tohearbeforeyoudie1|title=1000 albums to hear before you die: Artists beginning with T|work=guardian.co.uk|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media Limited]]|date=November 21, 2007|accessdate=May 29, 2013|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6GzRguEn2|archivedate=May 29, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> [[Allmusic]] editor [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] said that the album was innovative for eschewing the "sense of [[Swing (jazz performance style)|swing]] or [[groove (music)|groove]]" of previous guitar rock and New York punk albums for a "heady intellectual" scope that Television achieved instrumentally rather than lyrically. Erlewine asserted that "it's impossible to imagine post-punk soundscapes" without the album, which he said remains a "fresh" listen because of "how Television flesh out Verlaine's poetry into sweeping sonic epics."<ref name="Erlewine"/>

=== Rock guitar ===
Verlaine and Lloyd's dual guitar playing on the album strongly influenced [[the Strokes]],{{sfn|Schinder|Schwartz|2008|p=541}} alternative rock bands such as [[the Pixies]], [[noise rock]] acts such as [[Sonic Youth]], and big arena acts like [[U2]].{{sfn|Moon|2008|p=769}} In his work with U2, guitarist [[The Edge]] simulated their guitar sound by himself with an [[effects unit|effects pedal]].{{sfn|Moon|2008|p=770}} He said that he wanted to "sound like them" and that the album's title track had changed his "way of thinking about the guitar."<ref>{{cite news|last=Pattenden|first=Mike|date=January 2, 2010|url=https://login.thetimes.co.uk/?gotoUrl=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.thetimes.co.uk%2Ftto%2Farts%2Fmusic%2F|title=The Edge on guitarists, Glasbonbury and musicals|newspaper=[[The Times]]|location=London|accessdate=April 1, 2013}} {{subscription required}}</ref> [[Rob Sheffield]] of ''Rolling Stone'' called ''Marquee Moon'' "one of the all-time classic guitar albums" and said that the songs' tremulous, guitar twang shows how Television inspired bands such as [[R.E.M.]] and [[Joy Division]].<ref name="Sheffield">{{cite journal|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|authorlink=Rob Sheffield|date=October 16, 2003|page=90|title=Review: Marquee Moon|journal=Rolling Stone|location=New York}}</ref> Joy Division's [[Stephen Morris (musician)|Stephen Morris]] cited it as one of his favorite albums: "I just felt that ''Marquee Moon'' and the stuff from New York was odd, and it was different, and it was weird ... It still had a lot of energy".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thequietus.com/articles/05413-joy-division-new-order-stephen-morris-interview-favourite-records?page=3|title=Bakers Dozen: Joy Division & New Order's Stephen Morris On His Top 13 Albums|last=Hewitt|first=Ben|date=December 7, 2010|publisher=[[The Quietus]]|accessdate=October 17, 2012|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6G8cUhnLR|archivedate=April 25, 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> English guitarist [[Will Sergeant]] said that ''Marquee Moon'' was one of his favorite albums and that Verlaine and Lloyd's guitar playing was a major influence on his band [[Echo & the Bunnymen]].{{sfn|Adams|2002|p=169}}

